<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="negotiation">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>comms</group>
    <domain>communicator</domain>
    <summary>Interest-based negotiation replacing positional bargaining with mutual-gain problem solving using Principled Negotiation, BATNA/ZOPA analysis, and Cialdini's 6 Persuasion Principles.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>negotiation</tag>
      <tag>persuasion</tag>
      <tag>batna</tag>
      <tag>interest-based</tag>
      <tag>sales</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Negotiation and Persuasion</title>
    <summary>A framework for interest-based negotiation that replaces positional bargaining with mutual-gain problem solving. Core models: Principled Negotiation (separate people from problem, focus on interests, generate options, use objective criteria), BATNA/ZOPA analysis for leverage calculation, and Cialdini's 6 Principles of Persuasion for copy and influence. Tactical layer covers anchoring, silence, bracketing, the flinch, and the nibble.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Positional negotiation ("I want X") produces win-lose outcomes and damages long-term relationships. Fisher and Ury's research shows that interest-based negotiation consistently yields better outcomes for both parties because interests are usually more compatible than stated positions. Knowing your BATNA before negotiating is the single highest-leverage preparation step: it sets your walk-away point and eliminates desperation signals.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Salary or contract negotiations where you need a preparation brief</item>
        <item>Vendor, scope, or pricing discussions before a meeting</item>
        <item>Generating counter-argument libraries for price objections</item>
        <item>Writing persuasion copy (sales pages, pitch decks, outreach emails) using Cialdini principles</item>
        <item>Post-negotiation retrospectives to identify missed leverage</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Live real-time negotiations — agents prepare briefs; humans conduct the actual negotiation</item>
        <item>Legally binding contract drafting — agent output requires attorney review before signing</item>
        <item>Crisis or hostage negotiation scenarios — requires licensed human expertise</item>
        <item>When walk-away point is not yet defined — output will be generic without that anchor</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="principled-negotiation">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Separate the people from the problem: attack the issue, not the person, and allow the counterparty to maintain dignity throughout.</statement>
        <rationale>Attacking the person activates ego defense, which closes down creative solution space. Separating people from problem keeps both parties focused on the shared problem to solve.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Focus on interests, not positions: ask "Why is that important to you?" behind every stated demand to uncover the real need.</statement>
        <rationale>Positions are often incompatible; the interests behind them are usually compatible. A "non-negotiable deadline" (position) may mask "I need predictability for downstream planning" (interest) — which can be met with milestone check-ins rather than a fixed date.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Position vs interest analysis">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
POSITION: "I need a 20% raise"
INTEREST: "I need to feel valued and afford my mortgage"
→ Creative options: title change, bonus structure, equity, remote flexibility

POSITION: "Deadline is non-negotiable"
INTEREST: "I need predictability for downstream planning"
→ Creative option: fixed milestone dates with flexible final delivery
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Generate multiple options for mutual gain before selecting a solution — brainstorm without commitment, evaluate after.</statement>
        <rationale>Separating invention from decision prevents anchoring on the first reasonable option, which is rarely the best option for either party.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use objective criteria (market rates, industry standards, precedent) to evaluate options — never "because I want it".</statement>
        <rationale>Objective criteria depersonalize disagreement: neither party is wrong, the criterion is the arbiter. This preserves relationship while enabling firm positions.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="batna">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Determine your BATNA (Best Alternative To a Negotiated Agreement) before every negotiation — this sets your walk-away point and eliminates desperation signals.</statement>
        <rationale>Negotiators with no BATNA reveal desperation through concession speed and body language. A known walk-away point makes every offer evaluable against a real alternative.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Never reveal a weak BATNA — only disclose your BATNA when it is genuinely strong and will improve your position.</statement>
        <rationale>Revealing a weak BATNA destroys leverage and invites the counterparty to push harder, knowing you have no exit.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Weak BATNA: "I need this job, I have no other offers"
Strong BATNA: "I have two other offers and can freelance"
→ With a strong BATNA, state it: it shifts the counterparty's ZOPA estimate.
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="zopa-analysis">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Map the Zone of Possible Agreement before negotiating: if your walk-away and the counterparty's walk-away do not overlap, no deal is reachable and alternatives must be generated first.</statement>
        <rationale>Entering a negotiation where ZOPA does not exist wastes both parties' time and damages relationship. Identify the overlap — or the absence of one — before the meeting.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
You:   Walk Away $80K ←→ Target $95K ←→ Aspiration $110K
Them:  Aspiration $75K ←→ Target $90K ←→ Walk Away $105K
ZOPA:  $80K ←→ $105K  (overlap exists — deal is possible)
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="cialdini-principles">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Apply at most two Cialdini principles per message — stacking all six reads as a sales script and triggers skepticism.</statement>
        <rationale>Each principle works because it operates below conscious evaluation. Stacking them makes the pattern obvious, which activates resistance rather than compliance.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Reciprocity: give value first — offer a free audit, report, or consultation before asking for anything</item>
        <item>Commitment: get small yes agreements early — "Do you agree quality is important?" → "Does our approach improve quality?" → "Shall we proceed?"</item>
        <item>Social Proof: "Companies like [similar company] saw 40% improvement"</item>
        <item>Authority: cite credentials, data, and research — not just assertions</item>
        <item>Liking: find genuine common ground before disagreeing</item>
        <item>Scarcity: "Only 2 project slots left this quarter" — only use if true</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="tactical-moves">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Anchor first with a specific number, not a range — ranges anchor on the favorable end for the counterparty.</statement>
        <rationale>First numbers set the psychological reference point for the entire negotiation. Ranges like "$80K-$100K" anchor at $80K in the buyer's mind.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>After making an offer, stop talking — silence makes the counterparty fill the void, often with a concession.</statement>
        <rationale>Discomfort with silence causes most negotiators to soften their position before they need to. Holding silence is leverage that costs nothing.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Bracketing to reach a target number">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Target: $90K
Their offer: $80K
Counter: $100K
Expected midpoint: $90K  ← your target
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use the nibble (asking for small extras after the main agreement) only after the main agreement is signed, not before.</statement>
        <rationale>Pre-agreement nibbles signal that you are still bargaining on the main deal, which reopens closed points. Post-agreement nibbles are small enough that the counterparty's sunk cost prevents reopening.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="handling-hard-situations">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Respond to "Take it or leave it" by exploring the constraint behind the position, not by accepting or walking out.</statement>
        <rationale>"Take it or leave it" is almost always a posture, not a real constraint. Exploring what created the constraint often surfaces a creative option neither party had considered.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
"I understand this is your position. Help me understand
the constraints that led to it. Maybe we can find another way
to meet your needs while also addressing mine."
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Price objection responses">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
"Too expensive" → "Compared to what?"
"Over budget"   → "What is your budget?"
"Cheaper elsewhere" → "What else is different?"
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Accepting the first offer.</description>
        <reason>First offers are anchors, not final positions. Accepting immediately signals that the offer was too generous, which the counterparty will remember in future negotiations.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Negotiating complex issues over email.</description>
        <reason>Email removes tone and timing signals, which are 60-80% of negotiation information. Use email for documenting agreements, not for reaching them.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Anchor with a specific number, not a range — ranges anchor on the favorable end for the counterparty</item>
        <item>Send written summaries after verbal negotiations; ambiguity always benefits the more powerful party</item>
        <item>Never reveal your BATNA unless it is genuinely strong — revealing a weak BATNA destroys leverage</item>
        <item>Use the "nibble" only after the main agreement is signed, not before; premature nibbles signal desperation</item>
        <item>When generating Cialdini-based copy, pick at most two principles per message — stacking all six reads as a sales script and triggers skepticism</item>
        <item>For salary negotiations, always name a number first if you have good market data — the anchoring effect outweighs the risk of underselling</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="agent-integration-guidelines">
      <p>Use a two-subagent pattern: a research subagent gathers market data (comparable salaries, contract precedents, competitor pricing) and a drafting subagent synthesizes that data into a preparation brief using the negotiation template. For persuasion copy, a single call with Cialdini principle selection and copy generation is sufficient. Human review is mandatory before any real negotiation begins.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Human-in-loop before sending: any agent-drafted offer, counter, or persuasion message must be reviewed by the human before delivery — tone and relationship context cannot be fully captured in a brief.</statement>
        <rationale>The agent's BATNA and ZOPA analysis is only as accurate as the inputs; garbage in results in plausible-sounding but wrong brief out.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Simulated counterparties are too rational: real negotiators use emotion, ego, and politics — agent roleplay understates these factors.</statement>
        <rationale>Contract language suggestions from the agent are starting points, not final clauses; flag this explicitly in any output that includes contract terms.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>The agent cannot measure which Cialdini principle will be effective for a specific individual; A/B testing is required for persuasion copy.</statement>
        <rationale>Mechanical application of Cialdini tactics in copy can read as manipulative if the underlying offer is weak.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/negotiation-prep.txt" purpose="Full preparation template covering position, interests, BATNA, walk-away, counterparty analysis, creative options, and objective criteria"/>
      <template path="templates/zopa-calculator.py" purpose="Python function to compute ZOPA overlap from two walk-away values"/>
    </templates>
    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.pon.harvard.edu/daily/negotiation-skills-daily/"/>
      <link href="https://levels.fyi"/>
      <ref slug="stakeholder-communication"/>
      <ref slug="selling-ideas"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
